Project: No-Show Medical Appointments Analysis¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This dataset provides the attendance records for more than 100k medical appointments in Brazil, along with some additional characteristics about the appointments and associated patients.

The goal of this analysis is to find remarkable trends in no-show appointments and associated patients so that these trends can be used to predict whether the patient is going to show up for their appointment.

Questions:

  • Do females skip appointments more than males, or vice versa?
  • Is there a specific period of time where the proportion of no-show appointments is significantly higher?
  • Is there a certain weekday when the proportion of no-show appointments is unusually higher?
  • What is the range of age that shows the highest proportions of no-show appointments?
  • Is there a remarkably higher proportion of no-show appointments based on gender and age combined?
  • Is there a certain neighbourhoud where the number of no-show appointments is unusually higher?
  • Are there specific conditions of patients associated with no-show appointments?
  • Is there a lack of SMS messages associated with no-show appointments?

Assessment summary:¶

  • Extraneous columns: PatientId, AppointmentID, AppointmentDay
  • Incorrect spelling in columns: Hipertension and Handcap
  • Age cannot be a negative value
  • SchduledDay is of type string instead of datetime
  • In Handcap column, there should not be values other than 0 and 1.
  • In No-show column, values are 'No' and 'Yes' instead of 0 and 1.

Cleaning Data¶

Drop extraneous columns:

In [10]:
df.drop(['PatientId', 'AppointmentID', 'AppointmentDay'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Fix incorrect spellings in columns:

In [11]:
df.rename(columns={
    'Hipertension': 'Hypertension',
    'Handcap': 'Handicap'
}, inplace=True)

Drop rows with negative age:

In [12]:
df = df[df['Age'] >= 0]

Add column year_month. This makes it easier to group appointments by month later in analysis:

In [13]:
df['year_month'] = df['ScheduledDay'].str.slice(0,7)
df['year_month']

110524    2016-04
110525    2016-04
110526    2016-04
Name: year_month, Length: 110526, dtype: object

Change the data type of column 'ScheduledDay' from string to datetime:

In [14]:
df['ScheduledDay'] = df['ScheduledDay'].astype(np.datetime64)

In column 'Handicap', replace values larger than 1 with 1:

In [15]:
df['Handicap'] = df['Handicap'].apply(lambda v: 1 if v > 1 else v) # apply a function for each value in column

In 'No-show' column, change the values 'No' and 'Yes' to 0 and 1. This automatically changes the column's data type to int64:

In [16]:
df['No-show'].replace('No', 0, inplace=True)
df['No-show'].replace('Yes', 1, inplace=True)

Conclusions¶

In this analysis, we explored a dataset of more than 100k records of medical appointments and answered the following questions:

  • Do females skip appointments more than males, or vice versa?
    • No, there's no significant difference in proportions of noshow appointments between females and males.
  • Is there a specific period of time where the proportion of no-show appointments is significantly higher?
    • Yes, the proportions of no-show appointments in March and April are remarkably higher than May and June in 2016.
  • Is there a certain weekday when the proportion of no-show appointments is unusually higher?
    • No, there's no significant difference between the proportions of no-show appointments of weekdays.
  • What is the range of age that shows the highest proportions of no-show appointments?
    • The age range from 10 to 30 has the highest proportion of no-show appointments.
  • Is there a remarkably higher proportion of no-show appointments based on gender and age combined?
    • No, there's no significant difference between no-show proportions based on gender and age.
  • Is there a certain neighbourhoud where the number of no-show appointments is unusually higher?
    • No there's no specific neighbourhood where the proportion of no-show appointments is significantly higher.
  • Are there specific conditions of patients associated with no-show appointments?
    • Yes, significant proportions of no-show appointments are associated with patients who have diabetes, hypertension, or enrolled in Bolsa Familia welfare program.
  • Is there a lack of SMS messages associated with no-show appointments?
    • Yes, more than 56% of no-show records are associated with the lack of SMS messages.

Limitations¶

  • Removed one row contains negative age.
  • The "handicap" column had invalid values (values other than 0 and 1) that were replaced with 1.
  • In order for proportions to be meaningful, we excluded some values where the total number of appointments is not large enough to be significant. This is also noted with the visualizations below.

rects1 = ax.bar(x, noshow_proportions_per_age.values, width=width, color=['green', 'red', 'red', 'green', 'green', 'green', 'green', 'green'])

# Add some text for labels, title and custom x-axis tick labels, etc.
ax.set_ylabel('Appointments', fontdict={'fontsize':16})
ax.set_xlabel('Month', fontdict={'fontsize':16})
ax.set_title('Comparing proportions of no-show appointments for each age bin', fontdict={'fontsize':16})
ax.set_xticks(ticks=x, labels=labels)

fig.tight_layout()

plt.show()
  • We can see that the age range from 10 to 30 has the highest proportion of no-show appointments.

Are there specific conditions of patients significantly associated with no-show appointments?¶

Proportions of appointments of patients who have diabetes across no-show appointments:¶

In [42]:
# used examples from matplotlib docs
# https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/pie_and_polar_charts/pie_and_donut_labels.html#sphx-glr-gallery-pie-and-polar-charts-pie-and-donut-labels-py
# https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/pie_and_polar_charts/pie_features.html#sphx-glr-gallery-pie-and-polar-charts-pie-features-py

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 7), subplot_kw=dict(aspect="equal"))

# chart data and legend labels
data = df['Diabetes'][noshow].value_counts()
data_count = data.sum()
labels = ['No diabetes', 'Has diabetes']

# create the chart
wedges, texts, autotexts = ax.pie(data,
                                  # output the percentage along with the actual number of appointments
                                  autopct=lambda pct: str(round(pct, 2)) + "%\n(" + str(round(pct * data_count / 100)) + " appointments)",
                                  pctdistance=1.7, # distance of percentage text from center
                                  textprops=dict(color='black'), # color of percentage text
                                  colors=['darkgrey', 'red'], # colors of proportions in the chart in order
                                  explode=(.1,0) # make the important proportion stick out
                                 )

# set legend
ax.legend(
    wedges,
    labels,
    fontsize=14,
    loc="right",
    bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0, 0.5, 1.2) # position of legend
)

# edit the font of percentage text
plt.setp(autotexts, size=15, weight="bold")

# set chart title
ax.set_title(
    f"Proportions of patients who have diabetes across {data_count} no-show appointments",
    y=0, # put the title at the bottom of the chart
    fontdict={'fontsize': 16}
)

plt.show()
